DEATH OF DR. JOHNSTON. M.P.

Sir WILFRID LAURIER. Mr. Speaker, once again it is my very sad duty to have to inform the House that we have lost by death one of our colleagues. Dr. Johnston, the member for West Lambton, is no more. This is the fourth time during the present session that death has visited the members of this House. Nobody could have believed when we met here some ﬁve months ago that our late friend. Dr. Johnston, who then appeared to be the very incarnation of rugged health, would be one of the ﬁrst victims; but such is the uncertain tenure of life, that upon this, as upon many other occasions, the hand of fate has been laid upon him who looked to be the strongest. I need not say to the House that Dr. John-

ston was one of the popular members among us. He had no enemies; all his acquaintances were his friends; he was

beloved by those on this side, and I know he was equally respected by hon. gentle- men opposite. If there was any place where his high and sterling qualities were appre- ciated more than elsewhere it was in the town of ‘Sarnia and the county of West Lambton, where he passed the greater por— tion of his life. His death will be a sad blow to his friends, above all to his family, and I am sure that the members of this House on both sides will unite in tendering to his bereaved family the deep and sin- cere expression of their sympathy.

Mr. R. L. BORDEX. Mr. Speaker, on- behalf of those who sit at your left I join with what has been said by the Prime Min- ister. Our friend, Dr. Johnston, who has passed away, was a man of very kindly and genial disposition, and I cordially en- dorse what the right hon. gentleman has said as to the respect and esteem in which he was held by those who sit on this side of the House.

Sir WILFRID LATJRIER. I am informed that the body of Dr. Johnston will be re— moved from his place of residence in 0t- tawa to the train at half-past ﬁve o’clock. If it is agreeable to my hon. friend the lead- er of the opposition, T would ask that Mr. Speaker suspend the proceedings of the House at 5 o‘clock instead of 6 o'clock as usua .

Mr. R. L. BO‘RDEN. Certainly.
